Digitalis Dataset

Research question

Population: Patients taking digoxin prior to randomization

Exposure: Discontinuation of digoxin as per randomization

Outcome: Short-term (12 mths) risk / hazard ratio of hospitalization for worsened heart failure. OR Short-term (12 mths) risk / hazard ratio of death due to worsened heart failure.

Primary study

The Cox proportional-hazards model was also used to test for interactions between the study assignments and predefined variables that included the left ventricular ejection fraction, heart size, the cause of heart failure (ischemic vs. nonischemic), digoxin use before the trial, and New York Heart Association (NYHA) functional class.

Results: Fewer patients were hospitalized for worsening heart failure in the digoxin group (910) than in the placebo group (1180) (risk ratio, 0.72; 95 percent confidence interval, 0.66 to 0.79; P  0.001)

Table 3: Report subgroup analyses for previous use of digoxin but the outcome is death OR hosp for worsening heart failure.

Discussion: The risk of hospitalization, especially for worsening heart failure, was reduced with digoxin treatment. There were fewer deaths due to worsening heart failure in the digoxin group.

Censoring

As we only look at short-term we need to right censor our data, meaning that patients with an event after 365 days will be recoded to not having an event. Additionally, any observational days > 365 will be recoded to 365.
